#week-title("Three", "Observing Without Opening")

=== Core Teaching

The long work demands a mode of attention that the laboratory work so far has
not fully required: the ability to perceive meaningful change through glass,
without opening the vessel, without touch or smell, using only sight and
sometimes sound.

*What can be observed without opening:*

- *Colour change in the liquid:* The most accessible indicator. A liquid that
  was amber-gold in the first week may deepen toward brown, then toward a dark
  ruby, then begin to clarify. Any significant colour change is worth recording
  precisely, with date, estimated time of day (the heat of the day affects
  the circulation's activity), and comparison to previous observation.
- *The level of the liquid:* If the level is dropping significantly, the vessel
  has a slow leak. A stable level confirms the seal is holding.
- *Condensation on the glass:* The visible "sweat" of the preparation above the
  liquid line is a sign the circulation is active. In a well-sealed flask with
  good headspace, this should be present during the warmer parts of the day and
  may partially descend by morning.
- *The quality of light through the preparation:* A turbid liquid that begins
  to clear is a sign of separation occurring within the sealed vessel —
  the fixed is settling, the volatile clarifying. A clear liquid that becomes
  turbid may indicate new activity or the formation of a new phase.
- *Sound (very rarely):* In some preparations with significant volatile
  activity, a faint clicking or bubbling may be audible during the warmest
  hours. This is a sign of active internal circulation. It is not an emergency.

*What does NOT require opening the vessel:* almost anything. The tradition is
explicit that premature opening of a sealed circulation — from impatience,
from curiosity, from anxiety that "nothing is happening" — destroys the Work.
The conditions inside the sealed vessel build over time into a qualitatively
different environment from anything the open air would allow. Opening the vessel
releases this environment irretrievably.

*The long-work log as a discipline.* Recording observations weekly, even when
"nothing appears to have changed," trains the practitioner's perceptual memory
and eventually reveals subtle patterns that are only visible across many weeks.

=== Topics This Week

- Reading colour change, level, condensation, and transmitted light
- The weekly observation record: what to note and how to note it
- Why premature opening destroys the Work
- Training perceptual memory through the long-work log

#inner-work[
  *Sustained Attention as Practice*

  Sit with the sealed circulation vessel for fifteen minutes without doing
  anything. Simply observe it — its colour, its weight in your awareness, the
  subtle rhythm of its internal life.

  This is not a visualisation exercise. It is the same quality of receptive
  attention trained in the nature vigils of Year One Month 7, now applied to
  a prepared substance. Record one specific observation that arose during this
  sitting that you might not have noticed if you had looked only briefly.
]

